<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="65" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,398,785]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,280,398,424]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">Etymology</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Lepto, Greek" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1876" box="[298,426,398,424]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[298,426,398,424]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">Leptagrion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
= 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[462,527,398,424]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">Lepto</emphasis>
, Greek (λεπτός) for slender + 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[887,963,398,424]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">agrion</emphasis>
, neuter form of agrios (ἄγριος) meaning “wild”, which in damselflies is now used as an indicator that a genus belongs to the 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fliedner 2006)" baseAuthorityName="Fliedner" baseAuthorityYear="2006" box="[1073,1433,434,461]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Coenagrionidae (
<bibRefCitation author="Fliedner, H." box="[1263,1425,434,461]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" pagination="5 - 23" refId="ref15375" refString="Fliedner, H. (2006) Die wissenschaftlichen Namen der Libellen in Burmeisters &quot; Handbuch der Entomologie &quot;. Virgo, 9, 5 - 23." type="journal article" year="2006">Fliedner 2006</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. In reference to the slender abdomen of the species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,398,785]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,504,505,531]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">Generic characterization.</emphasis>
Medium sized 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fliedner" baseAuthorityYear="2006" box="[678,855,506,532]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Coenagrionidae</taxonomicName>
(
<quantity box="[870,996,506,533]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.55" metricValueMax="5.1" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" unit="mm" value="45.5" valueMax="51.0" valueMin="40.0">40–51 mm</quantity>
), pale postocular spots and pale occipital bar absent, rear of the head pale (presumably pale in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="St. Quentin" authorityYear="1960" box="[777,903,543,568]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auriceps">
<emphasis box="[777,903,543,568]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">L. auriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and an enlarged area black around the occipital foramen in 
<taxonomicName authority="Lencioni, 2022" authorityName="Lencioni" authorityYear="2022" box="[281,381,578,604]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vilelai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[281,381,578,604]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">L. vilelai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[389,479,578,604]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[389,479,578,604]" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
), cerci longer than S10, basal 2/3 “C”–shaped with the concavity internally, superior and inferior internal border of the “C” enlarged and apical extremity of cerci bifurcated (
<figureCitation box="[1151,1217,614,640]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1622,1646]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1173,1599]" captionTargetId="figure-477@3.[151,1436,1173,1599]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. A —Leptagrion auriceps: Appendages, mediodorsal view; B —Leptagrion macrurum: Appendages, mediodorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332333/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), the dorsal branch smaller and covered with brush–like setae, ventral one folded in an inverted “T” (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Santos" authorityYear="1979" box="[1103,1261,650,676]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Leptagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="2" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bocainense">
<emphasis box="[1103,1261,650,676]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="65">L. bocainense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) or “U”–shape (other species), inclined medially; paraproct vestigial (plate–like) and ental surface of penis S3 with a medio–longitudinal laminar process.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
